{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584907"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:59:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:59:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14832"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14832"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.65,0.19,0.02,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7523"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63517"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7523"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14832"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48971"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1003"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5020"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"9833"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18568"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63517"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following clotting factors requires Vitamin K for its synthesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Factor III","Factor IX","Factor XII","Factor V","Factor VIII"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVitamin K is a fat-soluble vitamin that is essential for the synthesis of several clotting factors in the liver. These include \u003Cstrong\u003EFactor IX\u003C/strong\u003E, as well as Factors II, VII, and X. A deficiency in Vitamin K can lead to bleeding disorders due to impaired synthesis of these factors. Symptoms of Vitamin K deficiency can include easy bruising, bleeding gums, nosebleeds, and prolonged bleeding from cuts. In severe cases, it can lead to gastrointestinal bleeding or intracranial hemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactor III\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as tissue factor, is not dependent on Vitamin K. It is a protein that initiates the clotting cascade by forming a complex with Factor VIIa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactor XII\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in the intrinsic pathway of the coagulation cascade and is not dependent on Vitamin K for its synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactor V\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the coagulation cascade but does not require Vitamin K for its synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactor VIII\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the intrinsic pathway and is not dependent on Vitamin K. It is associated with haemophilia A when deficient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin K is essential for the synthesis of certain clotting factors in the liver.","Factors II, VII, IX, and X are the clotting factors that require Vitamin K for their synthesis.","Deficiency in Vitamin K can lead to bleeding disorders due to impaired clotting factor synthesis."],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., Fausto, N., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (2014). Robbins and Cotran pathologic basis of disease, professional edition e-book. Elsevier health sciences","Imbrescia K, Moszczynski Z. Vitamin K. [Updated 2023 Jul 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551578/","Girolami A, Ferrari S, Cosi E, Santarossa C, Randi ML. Vitamin K-Dependent Coagulation Factors That May be Responsible for Both Bleeding and Thrombosis (FII, FVII, and FIX). Clin Appl Thromb Hemost. 2018 Dec;24(9_suppl):42S-47S. doi: 10.1177/1076029618811109. Epub 2018 Nov 14. PMID: 30428703; PMCID: PMC6714837."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48971"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14832"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48971"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-21T11:49:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T11:51:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7523"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63517"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1003"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Clotting